<h2><strong><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Community</span></strong></h2>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">For the past couple of years, Mark Stanislav, Senior Security Consultant at Rapid7, has been diving into Internet of Things (IoT) security research.&nbsp;<span>There's a long-winded excitement to IoT security research because in many      
        cases there are a number of technology components involved, including mobile applications, Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, device firmware, services, APIs, and a variety of network protocols.
              Each of these has the potential to provide a researcher with new insight into the operation of the device or become a critical foothold to take a next step in the research process.</span>&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/n0KM0mw02MQl0TN0Y6004N4"
>In a recent blog post</a>,&nbsp;Mark&nbsp;gave a high-level overview of what Internet of Things research entails, and where he    
        likes to get started with it - providing tips for anyone else that is interested in going down that path.
            He recommends beginning with a focus on mobile applications, network traffic, embedded hardware, and wireless communications.
            <a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/n0KM0mw02MQl0TN0Y6004N4"
>Learn more from his detailed blog post</a>.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Also popular in the community this month:<a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/R00l4Y6NM40020M0KnTNxQ0"
> a tu</a><a  href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/R00l4Y6NM40020M0KnTNxQ0"
>torial on easily assessing wireless networks with Kali         Linux</a>.</span></p>
